<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO COOK BARELA</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul  1 19:51:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
The war WAS a different war when you fought and when I fought. About halfway through that period about 6 guys who were Vietnam vets marched in a Peace demonstration, I think in NYC. The membership grew to 30,000. You may be correct, maybe they all weren't vets. I can't testify to that.<br><br>
Find the &quot;Winter Soldiers&quot; testimony in a net search and you will read veterans accounts of their own individual atrocities. It is not easy reading, but any who are students of the war are fooling themselves if they discount what these soldiers had to say. Vietnam opened my eyes to many things. You say you have not much knowledge of guys with PTSD. Many guys suffer from it. Read that testimony and you will see why.<br><br>
In 1967, when you fought, the majority of American people still supported the war in Vietnam. In 1970, when I was there, I didn't know very many who even knew what we were over there for. Morale was terrible. An example: guys lighting up smokes at night on perimeter guard out in the boonies, at times our positions were fast asleep. I was scared shitless. Big difference between Army and Marines. Army was many draftees like myself. Marines were more &quot;esprit de corps&quot;. <br><br>
Look at the outrage over WACO. I can draw the same parallels with Vietnam. <br><br>
Lastly. Don't ever think that there is anything that can be said or done that could ever bring dishonor to the names on the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. Why? ask anyone - pro Vietnam War or anti Vietnam War - who has visited that hallowed ground.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


